[Problem Analysis]
1. Problem Essence & Type:  
   - A straightforward year‐conversion problem. Given a year in the Holocene (Human Era, HE), convert it to the corresponding Gregorian year (either "BC" or "AD").  
   - Type: Implementation / Arithmetic.

2. Algorithm Choice & Rationale:  
   - By definition: HE = (Gregorian year) + 10000, but Gregorian has no year 0.  
   - For HE > 10000, the result is AD (HE − 10000).  
   - For HE ≤ 10000, the result is BC, with year = (10001 − HE).  
   - This handles the "missing year 0" in the BC/AD system.

3. Complexity Analysis:  
   - Time Complexity: O(1) (just a couple of arithmetic operations).  
   - Space Complexity: O(1).

4. Edge Cases & Pitfalls:  
   - x = 10000 → 1 BC (10001 − 10000 = 1).  
   - x = 10001 → AD 1 (10001 > 10000 so 10001 − 10000 = 1).  
   - x = 0 → 10001 BC.  
   - x = -10000 → 20001 BC.

[Code Implementation]
```cpp
/* 
  Conversion between Holocene (Human Era) and Gregorian calendar.
  For HE > 10000: AD (HE - 10000)
  For HE ≤ 10000: BC (10001 - HE)
*/
#include <bits/stdc++.h>
using namespace std;

int main() {
    ios::sync_with_stdio(false);
    cin.tie(nullptr);

    int x;
    cin >> x;
    if (x > 10000) {
        // AD era
        cout << "AD " << (x - 10000) << "\n";
    } else {
        // BC era, note the absence of year zero in Gregorian
        cout << (10001 - x) << " BC\n";
    }
    return 0;
}
```

[Problem Analysis]
1. Problem Essence & Type  
   We need to determine whether the decimal representation of 1/x terminates.  In base-10, 1/x is a finite (terminating) decimal if and only if x’s prime divisors are a subset of {2,5}.  
   Category: Number Theory / Math.

2. Algorithm Choice & Rationale  
   Repeatedly divide x by 2 while divisible, then by 5 while divisible.  If the remaining value is 1, x had no other prime factors ⇒ “YES”; otherwise “NO”.

3. Complexity Analysis  
   - Time Complexity: O(log x) (each division reduces x).  
   - Space Complexity: O(1).  
   These meet typical contest constraints for x up to 1e9.

4. Edge Cases & Pitfalls  
   - Given 2 ≤ x ≤ 1e9, no need to handle x=1.  
   - Large x with only factors 2 and 5 (e.g., 2^30·5^18) remains efficient.  

[Code Implementation]
```cpp
/* 
   Algorithm: Check if 1/x is a terminating decimal in base-10.
   Key idea: 1/x is finite ⇔ x has no prime factors other than 2 and 5.
*/
#include <bits/stdc++.h>
using namespace std;

int main() {
    ios::sync_with_stdio(false);
    cin.tie(nullptr);

    long long x;
    cin >> x;

    // Remove all factors of 2
    while (x % 2 == 0) {
        x /= 2;
    }
    // Remove all factors of 5
    while (x % 5 == 0) {
        x /= 5;
    }

    // If remaining factor is 1, then only 2 and/or 5 were present
    if (x == 1) {
        cout << "YES\n";
    } else {
        cout << "NO\n";
    }
    return 0;
}
```

[Problem Analysis]
1. Problem Essence & Type:  
   We have \(n\) jobs, each job \(i\) requires \(a_i\) minutes on a single “production” machine and then \(b_i\) minutes of “consumption” on infinitely many parallel servers. We must sequence the \(a_i\) tasks (only one at a time) to minimize the overall makespan (from start of the first production to end of the last consumption).  
   This is the classic single‐machine scheduling with delivery times problem, often denoted \(1|\,|C_{\max}\) with post‐processing times \(b_i\).

2. Algorithm Choice & Rationale:  
   A known optimal rule sorts jobs by non‐increasing \(b_i\). Intuitively, jobs with larger consumption times (tails) should start their consumption as early as possible. After sorting, we simulate production in that order, keeping track of:
   - the cumulative production time \(T\), and
   - the current maximum of \(T + b_i\).  
   The maximum of \(T + b_i\) over all jobs is the final makespan.

3. Complexity Analysis:  
   - Sorting: \(O(n \log n)\)  
   - One pass to accumulate times and compute the result: \(O(n)\)  
   Total: \(O(n \log n)\), \(O(n)\) extra space. For \(n\le 10^5\), this is efficient.

4. Edge Cases & Pitfalls:  
   - \(n=1\) trivially returns \(a_1 + b_1\).  
   - If several jobs have equal \(b_i\), any relative order among them is fine.  
   - Beware of potential integer overflow if we used 32-bit but since \(a_i,b_i\le100\) and \(n\le10^5\), sums fit in 32-bit; we still use 64-bit to be safe.

[Code Implementation]
```cpp
/* 
  Scheduling with tails (delivery times) 
  Optimal: sort jobs by descending b_i.
*/
#include <bits/stdc++.h>
using namespace std;
using ll = long long;

int main(){
    ios::sync_with_stdio(false);
    cin.tie(NULL);

    int n;
    cin >> n;
    vector<pair<int,int>> jobs(n);
    for(int i = 0; i < n; i++){
        cin >> jobs[i].first >> jobs[i].second; // (a_i, b_i)
    }

    // Sort by descending b_i (the consumption time)
    sort(jobs.begin(), jobs.end(), [](const pair<int,int>& A, const pair<int,int>& B){
        return A.second > B.second;
    });

    ll productionTime = 0;   // cumulative a_i
    ll result = 0;           // max(productionTime + b_i)
    for(auto &job : jobs){
        productionTime += job.first;
        result = max(result, productionTime + (ll)job.second);
    }

    cout << result << "\n";
    return 0;
}
```

[Problem Analysis]
1. Problem Essence & Type:  
   - Given a (possibly truncated) triangular sum S′ = (1 + 2 + … + n) − x, recover the missing floor number x.  
   - This is essentially solving for n in the triangular number T_n = n(n+1)/2 just exceeding or equaling S′, then computing x = T_n − S′ (with the caveat that x must be ≥1).

2. Algorithm Choice & Rationale:  
   - For each S′:  
     a. Estimate n using the quadratic formula n ≈ ⌈(√(8·S′+1) − 1)/2⌉ so that T_n ≥ S′.  
     b. Compute x = T_n − S′.  
     c. If x = 0 (which means S′ itself is exactly triangular and no floor was “missing”), increment n by 1 and recompute T_n and x.  
   - This gives guaranteed 1 ≤ x ≤ n.

3. Complexity Analysis:  
   - Time per query: O(1) arithmetic and sqrt. Overall O(T).  
   - Space: O(1).  
   - With T up to 1e5 and S′ up to 1e8, this is very efficient.

4. Edge Cases & Pitfalls:  
   - When S′ is itself a triangular number, the direct formula gives x = 0. We must then use the next triangular number.  
   - Careful with floating‐point rounding when computing n; we use `ceil` on the real solution of the quadratic.

[Code Implementation]
```cpp
/* 
  Problem H: Find the missing floor number x if sum of 1..n minus x equals S'.
  Key idea: Solve n(n+1)/2 ≥ S', then x = T_n - S'; if x==0, use next n.
*/
#include <bits/stdc++.h>
using namespace std;
using ll = long long;

int main() {
    ios::sync_with_stdio(false);
    cin.tie(NULL);

    int T;
    cin >> T;
    while (T--) {
        ll Sp;
        cin >> Sp;
        // Solve n(n+1)/2 >= Sp via quadratic formula
        // n ≈ (sqrt(8*Sp + 1) - 1) / 2, take ceiling
        double disc = sqrt(8.0 * Sp + 1.0);
        ll n = (ll)ceil((disc - 1.0) / 2.0);

        ll Tn = n * (n + 1) / 2;
        ll x = Tn - Sp;
        // If x == 0, Sp was exactly Tn; use next triangular
        if (x == 0) {
            n++;
            Tn = n * (n + 1) / 2;
            x = Tn - Sp;
        }
        cout << x << "\n";
    }
    return 0;
}
```

[Problem Analysis]
1. Problem Essence & Type:  
   We are given two periodic schedules (A and B), each alternating between "class" and "break" intervals. We need to compute the total length of time, over a horizon \[0, K), during which both A and B are simultaneously in their break intervals.  
   This is effectively an interval‐intersection problem on two sets of periodic intervals.

2. Algorithm Choice & Rationale:  
   - Enumerate all break intervals of A:  
     For each integer i starting from 0, A’s i-th cycle has break from  
       startA = i*(x+y) + x  
       endA   = startA + y  
     Clip each interval to \[0, K). Stop when startA ≥ K.  
   - Do the same for B, generating a sorted list of B's break intervals.  
   - Two‐pointer sweep over these two sorted interval lists. At each step, take the current A‐interval [lA, rA) and B‐interval [lB, rB), compute overlap if any, add to answer, then advance the pointer whose interval finishes first.  
   This runs in O(#breaksA + #breaksB), which is O(K/(x+y) + K/(p+q)) ≤ O(K).

3. Complexity Analysis:  
   - Time Complexity: O(K/(x+y) + K/(p+q)) = O(K) in the worst case (x+y and p+q are at least 2, so at most ~5×10^4 intervals each for K=10^5).  
   - Space Complexity: O(K/(x+y) + K/(p+q)) for storing the intervals.  
   These bounds comfortably fit typical contest limits.

4. Edge Cases & Pitfalls:  
   - Partially truncated break intervals at the end if they exceed K.  
   - No overlap at all → answer is 0.  
   - Very small K (even smaller than the first break start) → no generated intervals.

[Code Implementation]
```cpp
/* 
  Problem D: Overlapping Breaks
  Compute total overlap length of two periodic "break" schedules on [0, K).
  Technique: generate break intervals for each schedule, then two-pointer interval intersection.
*/
#include <bits/stdc++.h>
using namespace std;
using ll = long long;

int main() {
    ios::sync_with_stdio(false);
    cin.tie(nullptr);

    ll K, x, y, p, q;
    cin >> K >> x >> y >> p >> q;

    // Generate break intervals for schedule A: cycles of length (x+y)
    vector<pair<ll,ll>> A, B;
    ll cycleA = x + y;
    for (ll i = 0; ; i++) {
        ll start = i * cycleA + x;
        if (start >= K) break;
        ll end = start + y;
        if (end > K) end = K;
        A.emplace_back(start, end);
    }

    // Generate break intervals for schedule B: cycles of length (p+q)
    ll cycleB = p + q;
    for (ll j = 0; ; j++) {
        ll start = j * cycleB + p;
        if (start >= K) break;
        ll end = start + q;
        if (end > K) end = K;
        B.emplace_back(start, end);
    }

    // Two-pointer sweep to sum up intersections
    ll ans = 0;
    int i = 0, j = 0;
    while (i < (int)A.size() && j < (int)B.size()) {
        ll lA = A[i].first, rA = A[i].second;
        ll lB = B[j].first, rB = B[j].second;
        // Compute intersection
        ll L = max(lA, lB);
        ll R = min(rA, rB);
        if (L < R) {
            ans += (R - L);
        }
        // Advance the interval that ends first
        if (rA < rB) {
            i++;
        } else {
            j++;
        }
    }

    cout << ans << "\n";
    return 0;
}
```

[Problem Analysis]

1. Problem Essence & Type  
   - We have a permutation \(P\) of size \(2n\).  Building an undirected graph by connecting each node \(i\) with \(P_i\) yields exactly the disjoint cycle‐components of the permutation.  
   - We are allowed to swap any two entries \(P_i\) and \(P_j\).  A swap inside a cycle splits that cycle into two smaller cycles.  
   - We must ensure every connected component (i.e., cycle) has size at most \(n\).  Minimize the number of swaps.

2. Algorithm Choice & Rationale  
   - First decompose the permutation into its cycle‐lengths.  
   - For a cycle of length \(L\le n\), no operation is needed.  
   - For a cycle of length \(L>n\), each swap can split one cycle into two pieces; optimally we keep extracting chunks of size \(n\) until the remainder is \(\le n\).  
   - Hence the minimal number of splits (swaps) needed for a cycle of length \(L\) is  
     \[
       \bigl\lceil L / n \bigr\rceil - 1,
     \]  
     because \(\lceil L/n\rceil\) is the number of pieces and we need one less split than the number of pieces.

3. Complexity Analysis  
   - Time Complexity:  
     - Cycle decomposition: \(O(2n)\).  
     - Summation over cycles: \(O(\text{number of cycles}) \le O(2n)\).  
     Overall \(O(n)\).  
   - Space Complexity: \(O(2n)\) for storing the permutation and visited flags.  
   - This easily meets typical limits for \(n\le 10^5\).

4. Edge Cases & Pitfalls  
   - Cycles of length exactly \(n\) require 0 swaps (\(\lceil n/n\rceil - 1 = 0\)).  
   - Self‐loops \(P_i = i\) form cycles of length 1, also requiring 0 swaps.  
   - No benefit arises from swapping entries between different cycles, since that would merge cycles and not help reduce any large cycle below size \(n\).

[Code Implementation]
```cpp
/* 
   Problem: Split permutation-cycles so no cycle length > n using minimum swaps.
   Key Technique: Cycle decomposition + greedy splitting (each swap splits one cycle into two).
*/
#include <bits/stdc++.h>
using namespace std;

int main() {
    ios::sync_with_stdio(false);
    cin.tie(nullptr);

    int n;
    cin >> n;
    int N = 2 * n;
    vector<int> P(N + 1);
    for (int i = 1; i <= N; i++) {
        cin >> P[i];
    }

    vector<bool> visited(N + 1, false);
    long long answer = 0;

    // Decompose permutation into cycles
    for (int i = 1; i <= N; i++) {
        if (!visited[i]) {
            int len = 0;
            int cur = i;
            // Traverse this cycle
            while (!visited[cur]) {
                visited[cur] = true;
                cur = P[cur];
                len++;
            }
            // If cycle length > n, we need splits
            if (len > n) {
                // Number of pieces = ceil(len / n), swaps = pieces - 1
                int pieces = (len + n - 1) / n;
                answer += (pieces - 1);
            }
        }
    }

    cout << answer << "\n";
    return 0;
}
```

[Problem Analysis]
1. Problem Essence & Type  
   We have a two‐state “play Go (G)” vs. “play TFT (T)” process where each trial in state G succeeds (win) with probability p (causing a switch to T), otherwise stays in G; similarly in T it succeeds with probability q (switch to G), otherwise stays in T. We start in G. We need the probability that the \(x\)-th game is G.  
   This is a simple two‐state Markov chain.

2. Algorithm Choice & Rationale  
   Let \(f[n]\) = P(\(\)game \(n\) is G).  The transition is  
     from G: next is G w.p. \(1-p\), T w.p. \(p\);  
     from T: next is G w.p. \(q\), T w.p. \(1-q\).  
   Hence for \(n\ge2\):  
     \(f[n] = f[n-1]\,(1-p) + (1 - f[n-1])\,q = (1-p-q)\,f[n-1] + q.\)  
   This is a linear recurrence \(f_n = a\,f_{n-1} + b\), with  
     \(a = 1 - p - q,\quad b = q,\quad f[1]=1.\)  
   Solving gives (for \(p+q\neq0\)):  
     \(f[x] = a^{\,x-1} + \frac{q}{p+q}\Bigl(1 - a^{\,x-1}\Bigr)\;=\;\frac{q + p\cdot a^{\,x-1}}{p+q}.\)  
   Edge case \(p=q=0\) ⇒ never switch ⇒ always G ⇒ probability = 1.

3. Complexity Analysis  
   Time: O(1) (one pow call)  
   Space: O(1)  
   Easily fits contest limits up to \(x\le 10^5\).

4. Edge Cases & Pitfalls  
   - \(p=q=0\): avoid division by zero, answer = 1.  
   - Very small/large \(a^{x-1}\): underflows to 0, which is correct.  
   - Negative \(a\) (when \(p+q>1\)): pow handles alternating sign correctly.

[Code Implementation]
```cpp
/* 
   Author: Expert CP coder
   Algorithm: Two‐state Markov Chain closed‐form
   Key idea: f[n] = (1-p-q) * f[n-1] + q => solve linear recurrence
*/
#include <bits/stdc++.h>
using namespace std;

int main(){
    ios::sync_with_stdio(false);
    cin.tie(nullptr);

    double p, q;
    int x;
    cin >> p >> q >> x;

    // Edge case: p = q = 0 => never switch, always G
    if (p == 0.0 && q == 0.0) {
        // for any x, probability of G is 1
        cout << fixed << setprecision(10) << 1.0 << "\n";
        return 0;
    }

    double a = 1.0 - p - q;     // recurrence multiplier
    // Compute a^(x-1)
    double a_pow = pow(a, x - 1);
    // Closed‐form: (q + p * a^(x-1)) / (p + q)
    double ans = (q + p * a_pow) / (p + q);

    cout << fixed << setprecision(10) << ans << "\n";
    return 0;
}
```

[Problem Analysis]
1. Problem Essence & Type  
   - We have an \(N\times M\) grid of integers. We want to pick one element from each row (in order from row 1 to row \(N\)) so that the resulting sequence is strictly increasing.  
   - This is a classic dynamic programming problem on sequences with a monotonicity constraint.  

2. Algorithm Choice & Rationale  
   - Let row \(i\) (1-indexed) have sorted values \(a_i[0\ldots M-1]\). Define  
     dp\[i\]\[j\] = number of ways to choose from rows 1..\(i\) such that we pick \(a_i[j]\) in row \(i\).  
   - Transition:  
     dp\[i\]\[j\] = \(\sum_{k: a_{i-1}[k] < a_i[j]} \text{dp}[i-1][k]\).  
   - Because each row is sorted, for each value \(a_i[j]\) we can find via binary search how many entries in row \(i-1\) are strictly less, then use a prefix‐sum array on dp\[i-1\] to get that sum in \(O(1)\).  
   - Initialization: dp\[1\]\[j\] = 1 for all \(j\).  

3. Complexity Analysis  
   - Sorting each row: \(O(N\cdot M\log M)\).  
   - Filling DP: for each of the \(N\) rows, for each of the \(M\) entries, we do one binary search in the previous row (\(O(\log M)\)) and one prefix‐sum lookup. Total \(O(N\cdot M\log M)\).  
   - Space: \(O(M)\) extra for two DP rows and a prefix‐sum array.  
   - With \(N,M\le1000\), \(N M\log M\approx10^7\) is efficient under typical contest limits.  

4. Edge Cases & Pitfalls  
   - Rows may contain duplicate values; strict inequality excludes equals correctly via upper_bound on \(a_{i-1}\).  
   - If no valid sequence exists, the final DP sum will be zero.  
   - The modulo \(19260817\) is not prime, but we only use additions, so no inverse operations are needed.  

[Code Implementation]
```cpp
/* 
  Algorithm: DP with prefix‐sums and binary search per row 
  Key idea: dp[i][j] = sum of dp[i-1][k] for all a[i-1][k] < a[i][j].
  Use sorted rows + prefix sums + upper_bound.
*/
#include <bits/stdc++.h>
using namespace std;
static const int MOD = 19260817;

int main(){
    ios::sync_with_stdio(false);
    cin.tie(nullptr);

    int N, M;
    cin >> N >> M;
    vector<vector<int>> a(N, vector<int>(M));
    for(int i = 0; i < N; i++){
        for(int j = 0; j < M; j++){
            cin >> a[i][j];
        }
        sort(a[i].begin(), a[i].end());
    }

    // dp_prev[j]: dp value for previous row picking a[i-1][j]
    vector<int> dp_prev(M, 1), dp_curr(M);
    // Base case: for row 0, dp_prev[j] = 1

    for(int i = 1; i < N; i++){
        // build prefix sums of dp_prev
        vector<int> pref(M+1, 0);
        for(int j = 0; j < M; j++){
            pref[j+1] = pref[j] + dp_prev[j];
            if(pref[j+1] >= MOD) pref[j+1] -= MOD;
        }
        // compute dp_curr for row i
        for(int j = 0; j < M; j++){
            // Find how many in a[i-1] are strictly < a[i][j]
            int cnt = upper_bound(a[i-1].begin(), a[i-1].end(), a[i][j] - 1)
                      - a[i-1].begin();
            dp_curr[j] = pref[cnt];
        }
        // swap dp_curr and dp_prev for next iteration
        dp_prev.swap(dp_curr);
    }

    // Sum up dp_prev over the last row
    int answer = 0;
    for(int v : dp_prev){
        answer += v;
        if(answer >= MOD) answer -= MOD;
    }
    cout << answer << "\n";
    return 0;
}
```

[Problem Analysis]
1. Problem Essence & Type  
   – We have a fixed undirected graph of keys (the QWERTY letter‐only keyboard), edges connecting “adjacent” keys (including diagonals), and moving one finger along one edge costs 1.  
   – Starting positions: left finger on ‘F’, right finger on ‘J’.  
   – Given a target string S, we must type it in order, moving exactly one finger per character (typing itself costs 0), minimizing total movement time.  
   – This is a classic 2-finger typing DP on a small graph (26 nodes).

2. Algorithm Choice & Rationale  
   – First, build the adjacency graph of the 26 letters by placing them on an approximate 2D grid (three rows, indented as on a QWERTY keyboard) and connecting every pair whose Δx≤1 and Δy≤1 (excluding self).  
   – Precompute all‐pairs shortest paths on this 26-node graph via 26 BFS’s → dist[u][v].  
   – Let dp[x][y] = minimum cost so far if, after typing the prefix, the left finger is on letter x and the right on y. Initialize dp[F][J]=0.  
   – For each next character c, build a new dp2[.][.] by trying:  
     • Move left finger from x→c: dp2[c][y] = min(dp2[c][y], dp[x][y] + dist[x][c])  
     • Move right finger from y→c: dp2[x][c] = min(dp2[x][c], dp[x][y] + dist[y][c])  
   – After processing S, answer = min_{x,y} dp[x][y].

3. Complexity Analysis  
   – Graph build + BFS: O(26·(26+E)) → negligible.  
   – DP per test: O(|S| · 26 · 26 · 2) = O(|S|·1352). Since Σ|S|≤10^5, total ≈1.35×10^8 integer ops → fits in ∼1s in C++.  
   – Memory: O(26²) for dp, O(26²) for dist.

4. Edge Cases & Pitfalls  
   – Allow both fingers to occupy the same key (the DP handles x==y).  
   – Strings of length 1 are handled seamlessly by one DP step.  
   – Ensure the keyboard adjacency mapping matches the given example (e.g., from ‘F’ you can reach ‘R’,‘T’,‘D’,‘G’,‘C’,‘V’ in one move).

[Code Implementation]
```cpp
/* 
   2-Finger Typing on QWERTY Keyboard
   - Build adjacency on a 2D embedding of the QWERTY letter keys.
   - Precompute all-pairs shortest paths by BFS.
   - DP over (left_pos, right_pos) states for each character in the string.
*/
#include <bits/stdc++.h>
using namespace std;
static const int INF = 1000000000;
int distKey[26][26];

int main(){
    ios::sync_with_stdio(false);
    cin.tie(NULL);

    // 1) Map each letter to a 2D coordinate (approximate QWERTY layout)
    vector<pair<double,double>> pos(26);
    string row0 = "qwertyuiop";
    string row1 = "asdfghjkl";
    string row2 = "zxcvbnm";
    for(int i=0;i<10;i++)
        pos[row0[i]-'a'] = {double(i), 0.0};
    for(int i=0;i<9;i++)
        pos[row1[i]-'a'] = {double(i) + 0.5, 1.0};
    for(int i=0;i<7;i++)
        pos[row2[i]-'a'] = {double(i) + 1.0, 2.0};

    // 2) Build adjacency: any two letters within Δx≤1 and Δy≤1 are neighbors
    vector<vector<int>> adj(26);
    for(int u=0;u<26;u++){
        for(int v=u+1;v<26;v++){
            double dx = fabs(pos[u].first  - pos[v].first);
            double dy = fabs(pos[u].second - pos[v].second);
            if(dx <= 1.0 + 1e-9 && dy <= 1.0 + 1e-9){
                adj[u].push_back(v);
                adj[v].push_back(u);
            }
        }
    }

    // 3) Precompute all-pairs shortest paths by BFS
    for(int src=0; src<26; src++){
        for(int j=0;j<26;j++) distKey[src][j] = INF;
        deque<int> dq;
        distKey[src][src] = 0;
        dq.push_back(src);
        while(!dq.empty()){
            int u = dq.front(); dq.pop_front();
            for(int v: adj[u]){
                if(distKey[src][v] > distKey[src][u] + 1){
                    distKey[src][v] = distKey[src][u] + 1;
                    dq.push_back(v);
                }
            }
        }
    }

    int T;
    cin >> T;
    // dp arrays: 26 x 26 states
    static int dp[26][26], dp2[26][26];
    char startL = 'f', startR = 'j';
    int sL = startL - 'a', sR = startR - 'a';

    while(T--){
        string S;
        cin >> S;
        // initialize dp to INF
        for(int i=0;i<26;i++)
            for(int j=0;j<26;j++)
                dp[i][j] = INF;
        dp[sL][sR] = 0;

        // process each character
        for(char ch : S){
            int c = ch - 'a';
            // reset dp2
            for(int i=0;i<26;i++)
                for(int j=0;j<26;j++)
                    dp2[i][j] = INF;

            // transition
            for(int x=0;x<26;x++){
                for(int y=0;y<26;y++){
                    int cur = dp[x][y];
                    if(cur == INF) continue;
                    // move left finger x->c
                    int costL = cur + distKey[x][c];
                    if(costL < dp2[c][y])
                        dp2[c][y] = costL;
                    // move right finger y->c
                    int costR = cur + distKey[y][c];
                    if(costR < dp2[x][c])
                        dp2[x][c] = costR;
                }
            }
            // swap dp and dp2
            for(int i=0;i<26;i++)
                for(int j=0;j<26;j++)
                    dp[i][j] = dp2[i][j];
        }

        // answer = min over all end states
        int ans = INF;
        for(int i=0;i<26;i++)
            for(int j=0;j<26;j++)
                ans = min(ans, dp[i][j]);
        cout << ans << "\n";
    }
    return 0;
}
```

**Explanation of Key Steps**  
- We embed the QWERTY letter keys onto a 2D grid to determine which keys are “adjacent” (Δx≤1, Δy≤1).  
- BFS from each letter gives O(1) lookup for the movement cost between any two keys.  
- A 2D DP (`dp[leftPos][rightPos]`) tracks the best cost to type a prefix with the fingers at those positions; each new character causes two possible finger moves.

[Problem Analysis]
1. Problem Essence & Type  
   - We have a rooted tree of n nodes (server cluster), each node i carries a value \(a_i\).  
   - For any subtree rooted at \(u\), we define its “overload period” as the LCM of all \(a_i\) in that subtree.  
   - We must precompute the subtree‐LCM for every node and then answer \(q\) online queries of the form  
     \[
       u = (x + \text{lastans}) \bmod n + 1,\quad
       \text{output } \mathrm{LCM}(\text{subtree }u)\bmod 998244353
     \]
   - This is a tree + number‐theory (LCM via prime exponents) + “small‐to‐large” (DSU on tree) merging problem.

2. Algorithm Choice & Rationale  
   - Factor each \(a_i\) into primes via a linear sieve (storing \(\{(p,e)\}\) per node).  
   - Build the rooted tree (children lists).  
   - Traverse the tree in **post‐order** (iteratively to avoid recursion limits).  
   - **DSU on tree (“small‐to‐large”)**:  
     • Each node carries a pointer to a `map<int,int>` that records, for each prime \(p\), the maximum exponent seen so far in that subtree.  
     • Also keep the current subtree‐LCM modulo 998244353.  
     • When merging children, always merge the smaller map into the larger one (to achieve ~\(O(N\log N)\) total).  
     • Upon each exponent‐increase \(\Delta\), multiply the LCM by \(p^\Delta\) (mod 998244353).  
   - After merging all children, insert/update the node’s own prime factors the same way.  
   - Store the resulting LCM in an array `ans[u]`.  
   - Each query is then answered in \(O(1)\).

3. Complexity Analysis  
   - Sieving (spf) up to \(\max a_i\le5\cdot10^5\): \(O(A)\).  
   - Total prime‐factor pairs \(\sum \#\mathrm{pf}(a_i)\approx2.5\cdot10^6\).  
   - DSU merges each pair at most \(O(\log n)\) times ⇒ ~\(5\!×\!10^7\) steps.  
   - Fast exponentiation for each exponent‐delta is small (\(\Delta\le20\)).  
   - Queries: \(O(q)\).  
   - Overall fits within typical time/memory limits for \(n,q\le5\cdot10^5\).

4. Edge Cases & Pitfalls  
   - **Deep trees** (chain of length \(n\)): avoid recursion by iterative post‐order.  
   - **Large maps**: merging smaller into larger to bound complexity.  
   - **Modulo operations** on each exponent‐increase.  
   - Make sure to free child maps after merging to control memory.

[Code Implementation]
```cpp
/* 
  Compute subtree-LCMs in a rooted tree by DSU-on-tree (small-to-large merging).
  Each node’s value is factorized; we maintain for each subtree the max exponent
  of each prime and update the LCM mod 998244353 on the fly.
*/
#include <bits/stdc++.h>
using namespace std;
using ll = long long;
static const int MAXA = 500000;
static const int MOD = 998244353;

// fast exponentiation mod
ll modpow(ll a, ll e) {
    ll r = 1;
    while (e) {
        if (e & 1) r = r * a % MOD;
        a = a * a % MOD;
        e >>= 1;
    }
    return r;
}

int main(){
    ios::sync_with_stdio(false);
    cin.tie(NULL);

    int n, q;
    cin >> n >> q;
    vector<int> a(n+1);
    for(int i = 1; i <= n; i++) cin >> a[i];

    // read tree edges, build children list
    vector<vector<int>> children(n+1);
    for(int u = 2, p; u <= n; u++){
        cin >> p;
        children[p].push_back(u);
    }

    // 1) Linear sieve for smallest prime factor
    vector<int> spf(MAXA+1);
    vector<int> primes;
    for(int i = 2; i <= MAXA; i++){
        if(!spf[i]) {
            spf[i] = i;
            primes.push_back(i);
        }
        for(int p: primes){
            ll x = ll(i)*p;
            if(x > MAXA) break;
            spf[x] = p;
            if(p == spf[i]) break;
        }
    }
    // 2) Pre-factor all a[i]
    vector<vector<pair<int,int>>> fac(n+1);
    for(int i = 1; i <= n; i++){
        int x = a[i];
        while(x > 1){
            int p = spf[x], cnt = 0;
            while(x % p == 0){ x /= p; cnt++; }
            fac[i].push_back({p, cnt});
        }
    }

    // 3) Compute post-order iteratively
    vector<int> post;
    post.reserve(n);
    vector<pair<int,int>> stk;
    stk.reserve(n);
    stk.emplace_back(1, 0);
    while(!stk.empty()){
        auto &tp = stk.back();
        int u = tp.first;
        int &idx = tp.second;
        if(idx < (int)children[u].size()){
            int v = children[u][idx++];
            stk.emplace_back(v, 0);
        } else {
            post.push_back(u);
            stk.pop_back();
        }
    }

    // 4) DSU-on-tree merge
    vector<map<int,int>*> mp(n+1, nullptr);
    vector<ll> subtreeLcm(n+1, 1), ans(n+1, 1);

    for(int u: post){
        // if leaf => start new map
        if(children[u].empty()){
            mp[u] = new map<int,int>();
            subtreeLcm[u] = 1;
        } else {
            // pick the child with largest map
            int bigC = children[u][0];
            for(int v: children[u]){
                if(mp[v]->size() > mp[bigC]->size())
                    bigC = v;
            }
            mp[u] = mp[bigC];
            subtreeLcm[u] = subtreeLcm[bigC];
            // merge others into bigC
            for(int v: children[u]){
                if(v == bigC) continue;
                for(auto &pe: *mp[v]){
                    int p = pe.first, e = pe.second;
                    auto it = mp[u]->find(p);
                    if(it == mp[u]->end()){
                        (*mp[u])[p] = e;
                        subtreeLcm[u] = subtreeLcm[u] * modpow(p, e) % MOD;
                    } else if(it->second < e){
                        int delta = e - it->second;
                        it->second = e;
                        subtreeLcm[u] = subtreeLcm[u] * modpow(p, delta) % MOD;
                    }
                }
                delete mp[v];
            }
        }
        // incorporate u's own factors
        for(auto &pe: fac[u]){
            int p = pe.first, e = pe.second;
            auto it = mp[u]->find(p);
            if(it == mp[u]->end()){
                (*mp[u])[p] = e;
                subtreeLcm[u] = subtreeLcm[u] * modpow(p, e) % MOD;
            } else if(it->second < e){
                int delta = e - it->second;
                it->second = e;
                subtreeLcm[u] = subtreeLcm[u] * modpow(p, delta) % MOD;
            }
        }
        ans[u] = subtreeLcm[u];
    }

    // 5) Answer queries online
    ll lastans = 0;
    for(int i = 0, x; i < q; i++){
        cin >> x;
        int u = (int)((x + lastans) % n) + 1;
        lastans = ans[u];
        cout << lastans << "\n";
    }
    return 0;
}
```

Explanation of key steps:  
- We sieve for smallest prime factors and then factor each \(a_i\).  
- We build an explicit post‐order of the tree without recursion.  
- For each node in post‐order, we DSU‐merge its children’s prime‐exponent maps (always merging smaller into larger), updating the subtree LCM on the fly when any prime exponent increases.  
- Finally, we answer each query in \(O(1)\) using the precomputed subtree‐LCM array.

[Problem Analysis]
1. Problem Essence & Type  
   We have an N×M grid of integers.  A "prefix" is any strictly‐increasing choice of one element from row 1, then row 2, ..., up to row i (1≤i≤N).  We want to collect the sum of each such prefix (one per distinct choice of columns), then sort all these prefix‐sums and output the k‐th smallest.  
   This is essentially finding the k smallest path‐sums in a layered DAG (rows are layers, edges only go from a cell in row i to a strictly larger cell in row i+1).  Each path corresponds to a strict prefix.

2. Algorithm Choice & Rationale  
   We perform a best‐first search (a.k.a. Dijkstra‐like or k ‐shortest‐paths in a DAG) over the layered graph, but we do not need to explore all paths—only the first k by sum.  
   - Initialize a min‐heap with all M nodes in row 1 (each prefix of length 1).  
   - Repeatedly pop the heap to get the current smallest‐sum prefix.  Count it; when we've popped k times, that pop’s sum is the answer.  
   - Whenever we pop a prefix ending at (row r, col c) with sum S, if r<N we generate all valid successors in row r+1 whose value > grid[r][c], forming new prefix‐sums S+grid[r+1][c’] and push them into the heap.  
   Because k≤1000, even if each pop spawns up to M≤1000 children, total pushes ≲k⋅M≈10^6, which is fast enough with a binary heap.

3. Complexity Analysis  
   - Time: O(M log M) to insert the row‐1 nodes + O(k) pops + O(k⋅M) pushes, each heap‐operation O(log( heap_size))≤O(log(10^6)).  Overall ~O(k⋅M log(kM))≈10^6⋅20=2×10^7.  
   - Space: O(k⋅M) for the heap in the worst case (≈10^6 entries) plus O(NM) for the grid and sorting.  

4. Edge Cases & Pitfalls  
   - N=1: we just take row 1 values, sort, and report the k‐th smallest.  Our general method handles this naturally (no successors).  
   - Large values: sums can go up to N×10^8≈10^11, so use 64‐bit.  
   - Duplicate sums/paths: different paths may end at the same (row,col) but with different sums; we treat them as distinct heap entries.  

[Code Implementation]
```cpp
/* 
   Algorithm: Best‐first search (min‐heap) over a layered DAG.
   Each state is a strictly‐increasing prefix ending at (row, col) with accumulated sum.
   We push all row1 cells, then always pop the smallest‐sum prefix, count it,
   and generate its children in the next row (where next_value > current_value).
   Stop when we've popped k prefixes.
*/
#include <bits/stdc++.h>
using namespace std;
using ll = long long;

struct State {
    ll sum;
    int row, col;
    // Compare by sum for min-heap
    bool operator>(State const &o) const {
        return sum > o.sum;
    }
};

int main(){
    ios::sync_with_stdio(false);
    cin.tie(nullptr);

    int N, M, K;
    cin >> N >> M >> K;
    vector<vector<int>> grid(N+1, vector<int>(M));
    for(int i = 1; i <= N; i++){
        for(int j = 0; j < M; j++){
            cin >> grid[i][j];
        }
    }

    // For each row, prepare a sorted list of (value, colIndex)
    vector<vector<pair<int,int>>> sortedRow(N+2);
    for(int i = 1; i <= N; i++){
        sortedRow[i].reserve(M);
        for(int j = 0; j < M; j++){
            sortedRow[i].emplace_back(grid[i][j], j);
        }
        sort(sortedRow[i].begin(), sortedRow[i].end());
    }

    // Min-heap of states
    priority_queue<State, vector<State>, greater<State>> pq;
    // Push all row-1 prefixes (length = 1)
    for(int j = 0; j < M; j++){
        pq.push({ (ll)grid[1][j], 1, j });
    }

    // Extract k times
    int count = 0;
    while(!pq.empty()){
        State cur = pq.top(); 
        pq.pop();
        count++;
        if(count == K){
            cout << cur.sum << "\n";
            return 0;
        }
        // Generate successors in row = cur.row + 1
        if(cur.row < N){
            int rnx = cur.row + 1;
            int vcur = grid[cur.row][cur.col];
            // In sortedRow[rnx], find first whose value > vcur
            auto &vec = sortedRow[rnx];
            auto it = upper_bound(vec.begin(), vec.end(),
                                  make_pair(vcur, M+1));
            // Push all successors
            for(; it != vec.end(); ++it){
                ll newSum = cur.sum + (ll)it->first;
                pq.push({ newSum, rnx, it->second });
            }
        }
    }
    return 0;
}
```
